Quick Answer:
 Lambda Expressions in Java 8 are anonymous functions that let you treat behavior as data. They simplify code, reduce boilerplate, and integrate seamlessly with functional interfaces like Runnable, Comparator, and Predicate.

ðŸ”‘ Core Details of Lambda Expressions
Introduced in Java 8 to support functional programming.
Syntax:
 (parameters) -> expression_or_block


Requirements: Must be used with a functional interface (an interface with a single abstract method, e.g., Runnable, Callable, Comparator).
Purpose:
Pass code as arguments.
Write concise, readable logic.
Avoid anonymous inner classes.

ðŸ“˜ Multiple Examples
1. Simple Arithmetic
interface Add {
    int addition(int a, int b);
}

public class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Add add = (a, b) -> a + b;
        System.out.println("Sum: " + add.addition(10, 20));
    }
}

ðŸ‘‰ Output: Sum: 30

2. Runnable with Lambda
Runnable r = () -> System.out.println("Running in a thread!");
new Thread(r).start();

ðŸ‘‰ Eliminates verbose anonymous inner classes.

3. Iterating Collections
List<String> names = Arrays.asList("Sagar", "Copilot", "Java");
names.forEach(n -> System.out.println(n));

ðŸ‘‰ Output: Prints each name.

4. Comparator for Sorting
List<String> names = Arrays.asList("Sagar", "Copilot", "Java");
Collections.sort(names, (a, b) -> a.compareTo(b));
System.out.println(names);

ðŸ‘‰ Output: [Copilot, Java, Sagar].

5. Stream API with Lambda
List<Integer> numbers = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4, 5);
int sum = numbers.stream()
                 .filter(n -> n % 2 == 0)
                 .mapToInt(n -> n)
                 .sum();
System.out.println("Sum of even numbers: " + sum);

ðŸ‘‰ Output: Sum of even numbers: 6.

6. Predicate Example
Predicate<String> startsWithS = s -> s.startsWith("S");
System.out.println(startsWithS.test("Sagar")); // true
System.out.println(startsWithS.test("Java"));  // false


ðŸ“Š Advantages vs Considerations
Advantages
Considerations
Concise, readable code
Debugging stack traces harder
Enables functional programming
Overuse can reduce clarity
Works with Streams for declarative style
Requires functional interface
Eliminates anonymous classes
May confuse beginners


